Goal: Build a GitHub Pages–deployable web app called geo-bee-trainer that helps kids prepare for Geo Bee by learning and quizzing countries, cities/capitals, rivers, seas/lakes, mountains, using an interactive map. Use MapLibre GL JS + open data (GeoJSON/TopoJSON).

Tech Stack
	•	Vite + TypeScript
	•	No backend required (all data local in /public/data)
	•	Map library: maplibre-gl
	•	Optional helper libs:
	•	@turf/turf for geometry utilities (bbox, centroid, length, nearest point)
	•	polylabel for polygon label placement (label point inside polygon)
	•	topojson-client if we load TopoJSON
	•	Styling: simple CSS (or Tailwind optional, but keep it minimal)

Hosting
	•	Must deploy to GitHub Pages via GitHub Actions workflow
	•	The app must work with base path /geo-bee-trainer/ (vite base config)

Execution Plan (build in this order)
	1.	Scaffold + deploy baseline
	•	Create Vite + TypeScript app with required folder structure.
	•	Add MapLibre map shell, HUD shell, and responsive panel shell.
	•	Configure GitHub Pages deployment and verify base path /geo-bee-trainer/.
	2.	Data pipeline + unified entities
	•	Add sample source data in /public/data.
	•	Implement scripts/build-data.ts to generate entities.json with labelPoint + bbox.
	•	Guarantee deterministic output (`npm run build:data`).
	3.	Learn mode
	•	Load packs and render relevant layers.
	•	Click feature to inspect details.
	•	Add guided next-item flow.
	4.	Quiz engine foundation
	•	Implement question generation, answer validation, feedback states, Hint/Reveal/Next.
	•	Add normalization helper for names + aliases.
	5.	Quiz types (must ship at least 6)
	•	Implement the six required quiz types in sequence, reusing core engine.
	6.	Progress + spaced repetition
	•	Persist per-entity progress to localStorage.
	•	Add mastery buckets and lightweight progress display.
	7.	Polish + performance
	•	Lazy-load pack data, tune hit testing, improve touch targets and readability.

MVP gate (must be true before polish)
	•	Learn mode works for sample packs.
	•	Quiz mode supports at least 6 required quiz types.
	•	`npm run build:data` regenerates entities.json.
	•	App deploys and runs correctly on GitHub Pages with /geo-bee-trainer/ base path.

⸻

App UX Requirements

Global Layout
	•	Full-screen map
	•	Top HUD bar with:
	•	Mode switch: Learn / Quiz
	•	Pack selector: e.g. “Europe Countries”, “World Countries”, “Europe Capitals”, “Europe Rivers”, “World Seas”, “Mountains”
	•	Quiz type selector (only shown in Quiz mode)
	•	Score + streak + progress indicator
	•	Buttons: Hint, Reveal, Next
	•	Right/Bottom panel (responsive) for:
	•	Prompt text (“Name this country”, “Find Italy”, “Which countries border Germany?”)
	•	Answer input (text field) OR multiple-choice options
	•	Feedback area (✅ / ❌ + correct answer)

Learn Mode
	•	Map shows relevant layer(s) for current pack.
	•	Clicking/tapping a feature selects it and displays:
	•	Name
	•	Type
	•	Optional fact line if available
	•	A “guided learn” toggle: “Next item” cycles through entities and highlights them.

Quiz Mode (Multiple Quiz Types)

Implement these quiz types (at least 6):
	1.	Identify Highlighted (Type-in)

	•	App randomly picks an entity and highlights it on map (country polygon or river line, etc.)
	•	Kid types the name (case-insensitive, trimmed, ignore punctuation like “.” and extra spaces)
	•	Hint button reveals first 2 letters (then 3, etc.)

	2.	Identify Highlighted (Multiple Choice)

	•	Same as above but show 4 choices (1 correct + 3 plausible distractors from same pack)

	3.	Find on Map

	•	Prompt shows name (e.g., “Find Spain”)
	•	Kid clicks/taps the map
	•	Correct if clicked feature matches target (for polygons/lines) OR click is within a tolerance radius of the entity’s label_point (for points)
	•	Provide visual feedback (green flash for correct, red for wrong)

	4.	Capital Match

	•	For country-capital pairs:
	•	Either highlight a country and ask for its capital
	•	Or show a capital city point and ask “Which country is this the capital of?”
	•	Support both type-in and multiple-choice variants

	5.	Neighbor Quiz (Borders)

	•	Pick a country; ask: “Select all countries that border Germany”
	•	UI shows a list of candidate neighboring countries with checkboxes OR clickable countries on map
	•	Use adjacency data from a precomputed neighbors.json OR compute it offline and store results

	6.	Rivers & Seas Identify

	•	Rivers (LineString): highlight a river line and ask name (type-in or MCQ)
	•	Seas/lakes (polygon OR point label): highlight sea area if polygon exists, else use label_point with halo highlight circle

Optional (bonus) quiz types if time:
	•	“Which sea is west of Italy?” (simple directional logic using label_points)
	•	Timed sprint mode: “Answer 10 in 60 seconds”

⸻

Data Model and Files

Entity schema (unified)

Create a unified entity format for quiz engine:

type EntityType = "country" | "state" | "city" | "capital" | "river" | "sea" | "lake" | "mountain" | "region";

type Entity = {
  id: string;
  type: EntityType;
  name: string;
  aliases?: string[];              // e.g., ["UK", "United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland"]
  geometryType: "point" | "line" | "polygon";
  // GeoJSON geometry (optional if using external feature source)
  geometry?: GeoJSON.Geometry;
  // Always present: used for labels, hints, zoom targets, click scoring
  labelPoint: [number, number];    // [lon, lat]
  bbox?: [number, number, number, number]; // [minLon, minLat, maxLon, maxLat]
  props?: Record<string, any>;     // facts: capital name, river length, etc.
  packIds: string[];               // membership in packs
};

Packs config

/public/data/packs.json:

[
  { "id": "europe_countries", "name": "Europe: Countries", "types": ["country"], "defaultViewport": { "center":[10,52], "zoom": 3.5 } },
  { "id": "world_countries", "name": "World: Countries", "types": ["country"], "defaultViewport": { "center":[0,20], "zoom": 1.4 } },
  { "id": "europe_capitals", "name": "Europe: Capitals", "types": ["capital"], "defaultViewport": { "center":[10,52], "zoom": 3.5 } },
  { "id": "europe_rivers", "name": "Europe: Rivers", "types": ["river"], "defaultViewport": { "center":[10,52], "zoom": 3.5 } }
]

Geometry sources

Place data in /public/data/:
	•	countries_world.geojson (or countries_world.topo.json)
	•	countries_europe.geojson
	•	rivers_europe.geojson
	•	capitals_world.json (points)
	•	seas_world.json (at minimum label points)
	•	neighbors_world.json (country adjacency by id)

Important: even if geometry is loaded as GeoJSON features, the quiz engine should operate on Entity objects with a labelPoint always defined.

Label points / centroids strategy

Implement a preprocessing step (node script) that generates entities.json:
	•	For polygons (countries, seas, lakes): compute labelPoint using:
	1.	polylabel (best inside point), fallback to turf centroid
	•	For lines (rivers): compute labelPoint using:
	•	point at 50% of line length along polyline (turf along)
	•	For points (cities, mountains): labelPoint is the point itself

Store results into /public/data/entities.json.

Add scripts:
	•	npm run build:data to generate entities.json (and optionally simplified europe subsets)
	•	Keep it deterministic and fast

⸻

MapLibre Rendering Requirements

Base map style

Use a free style for dev (example MapLibre demo style is OK), but code should allow swapping style URL.

Layers

Render different map layers depending on active pack:
	•	Countries: fill + border
	•	Rivers: line layer
	•	Points (capitals/mountains): circle layer + optional text label layer at high zoom

Highlighting

Highlight currently selected / quiz-target entity:
	•	Countries (polygon): change fill color + thicker outline
	•	Rivers (line): thicker line + glow outline line underneath
	•	Points: larger circle + halo

Implementation preference:
	•	Use setFilter() on a highlight layer (fast and simple), keyed by feature id/name
	•	Or feature-state if using vector sources; but with GeoJSON, filter layers are fine

Hit testing

For Find-on-map:
	•	For polygons/lines: use map.queryRenderedFeatures(e.point, { layers: [...] })
	•	For points: allow nearest labelPoint within radius (e.g., 30px, scale by zoom)

⸻

Spaced Repetition / Progress Tracking

Persist user progress in localStorage:
	•	seenCount, correctCount, streak, lastSeen, lastResult
	•	Simple scheduling:
	•	if wrong → show again soon
	•	if correct several times → show less often
	•	Provide a progress view:
	•	“Mastered / Learning / Needs practice”
	•	Map coloring by mastery for countries (optional but nice)

